[2] Liberia: Ebola recurrence
Date: Tue 24 Nov 2015
Source: Thomson Reuters Foundation [edited]
http://www.trust.org/item/20151124120842-lvfdw/


The index patient, a 15-year-old, succumbed to Ebola virus disease (EVD) late on Mon 23 Nov 2015. He is the 1st to die from EVD for months in Liberia. It is not known how patient NG was infected, but investigations are underway.

According to a health expert who spoke on Tue 24 Nov 2015, there was a failure to transfer a suspected patient with EVD directly to a specialist treatment unit. The fresh outbreak of EVD in Liberia may reflect fatigue and complacency among health-care workers.

According to Medecins Sans Frontieres (MSF) representative Carissa Guild, the 15-year-old index patient, "...went to several health-care centers before being referred to an Ebola treatment unit. Several health workers who cared for him may have not worn protective equipment. MSF's Guild said "Normally with a surveillance system, if someone has signs and symptoms (of Ebola) they would not be hospitalized but would be immediately sent to an Ebola treatment center to be tested. There were no cases for a while, and Liberia was nearing the end of a 90-day period of heightened surveillance... it is quite possible that people were tired and got complacent."

It is unlikely cross-border contamination occurred; Guinea has no EVD cases, and Sierra Leone was declared EVD-free on 2 Nov 2015 after 42 days without a case.

The recurrence of EVD in Liberia, after twice previously declared EVD-free only to have new EVD cases appear is a reminder for the EVD-affected countries to remain vigilant for recurrence. According to UNICEF (United Nations Children's Fund) representative Sheldon Yett, "Everyone celebrates when the last case is treated, but we can't let our guard down. There will be other fires; we need to be ready for them too."

[Byline: Kieran Guilbert]

