[The total number of confirmed cases in Guinea, Sierra Leone, and Liberia to 22 Nov 2015 is 28 601 including 11 299 deaths. This number does not include the latest death in Liberia but does include 3 cases in the past 21 days in the country. The complete situation report, including tables and figures, is available at the source URL above. - Mod.LK]

******
[5] ECDC [European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control]
Date: Mon 23 Nov 2015
Source: ECDC [edited]
http://goo.gl/CpmdTj


Background
---------
An epidemic of Ebola virus disease (EVD) has been ongoing in West Africa since December 2013, mainly affecting Guinea, Liberia and Sierra Leone. On 8 Aug 2014, WHO declared the Ebola epidemic in West Africa a Public Health Emergency of International Concern (PHEIC). As of 18 Nov 2015, WHO has reported 28 598 cases of Ebola virus disease related to the outbreak in West Africa, including 11 299 deaths [1]. The number of cases in the most affected countries peaked in autumn 2014 and has been slowly decreasing since then. Liberia was declared Ebola-free by WHO on 3 Sep 2015 and Sierra Leone on 7 Nov [2015]. Guinea has not reported new cases since 29 Oct 2015.

Current situation in Liberia
---------------
On 20 Nov 2015, the Liberian Ministry of Health and Social Welfare reported 3 confirmed cases of Ebola virus disease [2]. On 19 Nov 2015, a reference laboratory in Liberia reported an Ebola positive result in a sample from a patient who presented symptoms such as fever, weakness and bleeding at a hospital in Monrovia on 17 Nov 2015. The patient was placed in isolation. The Liberian Ministry of Health and Social Welfare stated in a press release that 4 patients and high risk contacts are being cared for at an Ebola Treatment Unit in Monrovia. The hospital where the patient was detected is undergoing decontamination, and all health care workers who were in contact with the patient are being monitored.

According to media, the 1st case is a boy with onset of symptoms on 14 Nov 2015 [3,4], who attended school on Mon 16 Nov 2015, was admitted to a hospital on 17 Nov 2015 and confirmed positive on 2 samples on 19 Nov 2015. Two additional cases have been identified among family members. As of 20 Nov 2015, 4 patients (corresponding to at least 3 confirmed cases) and high risk contacts are hospitalised in an Ebola Treatment Unit in Monrovia. According to media, 153 contacts presenting with high, medium and low-risk exposure are followed-up [5]. Further response activities and contact tracing are ongoing.

Assessment
---------
Liberia was declared free of Ebola virus transmission in the human population on 3 Sep 2015, following which, Liberia entered a 90-day period of EVD heightened surveillance [6]. The confirmation of new EVD cases during heightened surveillance periods after the tail end of outbreaks is not unexpected as stated in the most recent ECDC risk assessments [7,8].

The identification of new cases in Liberia highlights the importance of maintaining enhanced surveillance and immediate response capacity for control in the aftermath of the Ebola epidemic in the affected countries.

Ebola outbreak in Africa pages

(Rapid risk assessment: Outbreak of Ebola virus disease in West Africa. 13th update, 13 Oct 2015. [Internet]. Stockholm: ECDC; 2015)

