[6] Suspected, vaccines, research, technology, funding

23 Nov 2015: 1st systematic review of Ebola risks underway
http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2015/11/151123102100.htm
[The study found caring for people with late-stage Ebola virus disease (EVD) at home and preparing deceased Ebola victims for burial, puts people at greatest risk of contracting the disease. A new paper on risk factors for transmitting EVD recommends better provision of health care facilities to ensure that people with the disease don't have to be cared for at home.
Full reference: Brainard L, Hooper K, Pond K, Hunter, PR (23 Nov 2015). Risk factors for transmission of Ebola or Marburg virus disease: a systematic a systematic review and meta-analysis_ International Journal of Epidemiology¬, 2015; dyv307. review and meta-analysis. _International Journal of Epidemiology_, 2015; dyv307 DOI: 10.1093/ije/dyv307
http://ije.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2015/11/20/ije.dyv307.full.pdf+html]

24 Nov 2015: Liberia resurgence: The changing meaning of 'Ebola-free'
http://www.eboladeeply.org/articles/2015/11/8515/liberia-resurgence-changing-meaning-ebola-free/
[Website Ebola Deeply examines what "Ebola-free," in reality, means, and what might be better definitions.
Bruce Aylward, the WHO's Special Representative for the Ebola Response, said in Geneva last week: "As they confirm that they've stopped transmission, these countries are downgrading from a state of emergency to a state of alert. It's so important to them to get back on their feet, economically and psychologically as well. ...
Aylward added that in the current context, Ebola-free ceremonies should mark the end of original chains of transmission instead of suggesting the eradication of the virus. Subsequent flare-ups should be treated as rare but inevitable, he said.]

Non-governmental organization
------------------
25 Nov 2015: Air Partner winds down Ebola relief work after more than a year as Sierra Leone is declared Ebola-free
http://www.incentivetravel.co.uk/news/airportairline/30120-air-partner-winds-down-ebola-relief-work-after-more-than-a-year-as-sierra-leone-is-declared-ebola-free
[Air Partner has worked continuously with governments, NGOs and aid agencies since the Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreak began to provide the affected countries with vital supplies. Between 26 Oct 2014 and 11 Nov 2015, the freight team operated a total of 128 flights between the UK and Freetown, Sierra Leone. The Private Jets division is still operating a helicopter on a wet lease. At the peak of the crisis, the group was operating flights every 48 hours carrying cargo of medical equipment and supplies, vehicles, construction materials, and protective clothing.]

